  "answer": "Here's a famous *maqtā* (signature couplet) from Ghalib's first ghazal in the *Diwan*:\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nTu ne qasam *mai-kashi* ki khaayi hai Ghalib  \nTeri qasam ka kuch *aitbaar* nahin hai[^1]\n\n**Translation:**  \nYou've sworn an oath, O Ghalib, to give up the wine,  \nBut in your vow, the faith of any prayer is not there.[^2]\n\nThis sher exemplifies Persian-Urdu code-switching **within each line**. In the first misra (*Tu ne qasam mai-kashi ki khaayi hai Ghalib*), the matrix is everyday Urdu/Hindustani syntax and vocabulary (\"tu ne ... ki khaayi hai,\" a casual construction meaning \"you have taken/made\"), which delivers the direct, punchy accusation of hypocrisy. The Persian lexical insertion *mai-kashi* (wine-drinking, a sophisticated compound noun evoking classical Persian poetic tropes of bacchanalia) elevates the register, providing the culturally resonant, elevated concept of the vice.  \n\nThe second misra reverses emphasis slightly (*Teri qasam ka kuch aitbaar nahin hai*), with Urdu framing the negation (\"teri qasam ka ... nahin hai\") for punchy dismissal, while the Persian *aitbaar* (reliability/trust, another high-register term from Persian philosophical/literary discourse) adds ironic depth to the faithlessness. Overall, **Persian sets the refined, philosophical-poetic register (concepts like vinous indulgence and trustworthiness), while Urdu carries the punch (colloquial directness and emotional sting)**—a hallmark of Ghalib's Rekhta style, blending Persian sophistication with vernacular immediacy.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/01-aa-ke-meri-jaan-ko-qarar-nahin-hai/transliteration/#p-2ecbcd).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/01-aa-ke-meri-jaan-ko-qarar-nahin-hai/translation/#p-4304e1).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 1, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/01-aa-ke-meri-jaan-ko-qarar-nahin-hai/transliteration/).",
